{"type":"message","id":"8b2138e5","parentId":"6fe08af4","timestamp":"2026-05-12T09:29:15.606Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I notice something in the curl output. It shows the Authorization header is truncated:\n\n```\n> Authorization: Bearer sk-cp-…S3DZ\nX49cR57CdVUjj8pEAvt_EVQ8A5fAvY\n```\n\nWait, it seems like there's a line break in the middle of the token! `ORS3DZ\\nX49cR57CdVU...` — the `\\n` might be a newline in the actual token.\n \nOh, I see what happened now. The request body shows `Content-Length: 2` but the actual body was `{}` based on the earlier output — something went wrong with how the JSON was encoded in PowerShell. The `curl: (3) bad range specification in URL position 51` error is actually a PowerShell artifact, not from curl itself.\n\nLooking at the verbose output more carefully, the real issue is that the Authorization header got corrupted with a newline character inserted in the middle of the token string — it shows `ORS3DZ` followed by `X49cR57CdV` on the next line, which is definitely breaking the authentication. I think the real problem is how the token string is being passed through the shell - there might be a newline or whitespace issue corrupting the authorization header. Let me try using Python to make the request directly and see if that avoids the shell interpretation problems.\n","thinkingSignature":"29a68b810f5467798654c756b707e7f192fbe1387549fd71ea2440c52a5b5bc5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_cy7452y60a4a_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"import urllib.request,urllib.parse,json; r=urllib.request.Request('https://api.minimax.io/anthropic/v1/messages',data=json.dumps({'model':'MiniMax-M2.7','max_tokens':10,'messages':[{'role':'user','content':'hi'}]}).encode(),headers={'Authorization':'Bearer sk-cp-s-RwpSrtMhHuWDdPPS1dpYW4JvXSdR3W890ibdNp6AGGxs19bAmsahQ955b6OQTe_GGRc6iieHJB163OdegORS3DZX49cR57CdVUjj8pEAvt_EVQ8A5fAvY','Content-Type':'application/json'}); print(